\begin{abstract}

In this work, we study an alternative approach for capping and pricing carbon emissions in electric markets: the cap-and-trade paradigm with re-trade of allowances. We model the electric market (generators and allowances' auctioneer) as a two stage stochastic capacity expansion equilibrium problem, where we allow future investment and re-trading of emission permits among generators. The model studies generation and future investments in the electric sector in two regimes of demand: deterministic and stochastic. The configuration enforces the reduction of carbon emissions by setting a carbon budget, which allows to assess the impact of green policies and pledges concerning an electric system. We use the proposed model to analyze the Chilean electric sector under a cap-and-trade paradigm as an alternative to the existing carbon tax. We show that the Chilean pledge regarding emissions reductions does not encourage a shift to greener technologies. Moreover, we characterize two strategies to comply with the renewable targets by mid-century. On the one hand, a stringent carbon budget that induces high price of carbon permits and phases out coal-based generators. On the other hand, a less stringent target which significantly encourages investment in renewable technologies, but with low remaining shares of coal-based electric generation towards 2050.



%Finally, we demonstrate that under technology change costs reductions, higher demand scenarios will relax the need for stringent carbon budgets to achieve new renewable energy investments and hence meet the Chilean pledges. These results suggest that some aspects of the Chilean pledge require further analysis, of the economic impact, particularly with the recent announcement of achieving carbon neutrality towards 2050. 
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

The groundbreaking work from Eunice Foote \cite{Foote1856} linked, for the first time 150 years ago, \acrshort*{co2} emissions\footnote{Hereafter, we will use ``\acrshort*{co2}'' and ``carbon'' interchangeably} and the possible rise of temperature in Earth's atmosphere. Fast forward to present time, the climate crisis has been well established, where efforts have been directed towards avoiding the worst case climate scenarios. However, there is still much to do, particularly in the energy sector, where global energy-related carbon emissions reached in 2018 a historic high of 33.1 GtCO$_2$ \cite{IEA2019}. This is one of the reasons why energy sector's decarbonization strategies have been the focus of a vast number of studies, being carbon pricing one of the main mechanism to accomplish such a goal \cite{Robert2019Carbon}. 
\smallskip 

%{\color{red} make sure cap-and-trade and cap-and-trade is consistent}

%{\color{red} Checked!}

There are two main types of carbon pricing strategies, a carbon tax based mechanism and a cap-and-trade (or emissions trading system, \acrshort*{ets}). In both cases, the main goal is to create incentives to spur investment of green technologies and to reduce the participation of polluting fossil-fueled generators \cite{Chen2011}. Both pricing methods have been extensively studied in the literature, and several countries have already implemented at least one of them (see \cite{Narassimhan2018}, and references therein, for a review of the methods and their implementation). The decision of which of the two is the most suitable climate policy option for a certain country generally depends on aspects such as political support and administrative costs \cite{goulder2013carbon}.
\smallskip

Nevertheless, in terms of the climate crisis, there is a global goal, summarized in the Paris Agreement, signed by 169 countries: to ``keep a global temperature rise this century well below 2 $^{\circ}$C above pre-industrial levels and to pursue efforts to limit the temperature increase even further to 1.5 $^{\circ}$C''.\footnote{ https://unfccc.int/process-and-meetings/the-paris-agreement/the-paris-agreement} Participating countries of this agreement submitted voluntarily their \acrlong*{ndc} (\acrshort*{ndc}) with goals according to each economic reality. However, despite the effort, it has been shown that the  \acrshort*{ndc}s alone are insufficient (see \cite{rogelj2016paris}). Hence, experts have urged for stricter actions and a massive adjustment in how the world produces its energy in order to meet climate change goals. In this context, cap-and-trade strategies provide an advantage over a carbon tax. By setting a carbon budget available for a country in a given time interval, the carbon trading market must comply with an enforced level of emissions reductions, which can be further linked with global or regional targets, such as temperature targets \cite{feijoo2020,feijoo2019climate,Binsted2019}. On the contrary, the carbon tax mechanism puts a price on carbon, and the market adjusts accordingly. However, such a price might not necessarily induce a reduction of emissions to the desired level. 
\smallskip

The literature and lessons on cap-and-trade strategies is vast (see \cite{schmalensee_lessons_2017}), particularly that contextualized on the emissions from the electric sector \cite{feijoo2014design,Feijoo2015Microgrid}.   
Some notable examples, relevant in the context of our paper, are \cite{yihsu2005oligopolistic} and \cite{zhao2010longct}. Authors in \cite{yihsu2005oligopolistic} were among the first to propose a game theoretical approach (Mixed Complementarity Problem, \acrshort*{mcp}) to study the strategic actions of emitting units when facing future emissions obligations, forward contracts and a operating reserve market. Their proposed deterministic model assumes a free allowance allocation approach, where generators can then either buy or sell excess of allowances in a trading market. Researchers in \cite{zhao2010longct} also proposed a game theoretical approach (similar to that in \cite{yihsu2005oligopolistic}) where different allowance allocation rules (capacity-based potential emission, capacity-based actual emission or sales-based output rule) were tested. A different modeling approach was taken by \cite{limpaitoon2011impact}. Authors proposed a bi-level model where an emissions cap constraint is explicitly set for the market operator agent (lower level of the bi-level model), where its dual variable sets the price that generators face for their emissions. However, authors considered neither an allowance allocation mechanisms nor a trading market. Authors in \cite{Wang2015}, using a computable general equilibrium model, studied the Copenhagen target through carbon emission trading for a province in China. As researchers above, this study also considered a free allowances allocation mechanism, followed by emissions trading strategies. They conclude that inclusion of trading markets in the models are decisive to mitigate further economic losses produced by systems with stringent carbon caps. 
Another feature studied by several authors in cap-and-trade systems is the inclusion of uncertainties at different levels, including hard and expected emissions constraints, stochastic future carbon prices, uncertain systems (such as load and renewable-supply variability), and environmental policy  \cite{mavromatidis2018design,cristobal2013stochastic,jin2019low}.
However such models do not necessarily consider a carbon market, and hence, they just consider a cap constraint. All these market design and mathematical approaches described above have been used to study regional context such as China \cite{liu2017impact}, the European Union (EU) ETS \cite{chen2012greenhouse}, and the U.S. \cite{chen2012greenhouse,rocha2015impact}.
\smallskip
%boffino2019two

From the theoretical perspective, the modeling approach that we develop follows  \cite{ehrenmann_generation_2011}, but departs from it in a similar fashion as  \cite{daertrycke_risk_2017}, by proposing a model with risk neutral agents. We concentrate the analysis in the study of a cap-and-trade configuration where, in contrast to the precedent literature, there are multiple periods and re-trade of allowances among generators. Thus, an allowance represents a real asset in positive net supply that is risk free. Consequently, when there is uncertainty, our model proposes a simple configuration where markets are possibly incomplete. Furthermore, we consider another source of incompleteness given by restricted (segmented) participation in the allowances market. Segmentation in financial markets could be used as a trading mechanism in policies targeted to more efficient outcomes as risk trading mechanisms in \cite{mays_asymmetric_2019}. In a competitive setting, exogenous restrictions, as the one given by a quota, were introduced by \cite{Cass2006}. Endogenous restrictions were initially analyzed in \cite{Cassetal2001}. Nevertheless, the case of endogenous investment restrictions was not included until \cite{cea-echenique_general_2018}.
\smallskip

Based on the literature, this paper proposes an alternative two-stage Stochastic Mixed Complementarity Problem (\acrshort*{smcp}) that can be used to study the effect of defined carbon budgets for both local and global energy systems. The proposed model includes several features, described in the previous paragraphs, that have been previously studied disjointedly. We put together a long-term capacity investment model with demand and emissions budget uncertainty, trade and re-trading of allowances with all prices being determined endogenously. The \acrshort*{smcp} model presented here considers uncertainties regarding future demand levels and the actual remaining carbon budget or available carbon credits. Furthermore, the model actually considers a cap-and-trade market in two stages, allowance allocation market followed by a trading market (re-trade), unlike many existing studies that mostly consider the cap component of a cap-and-trade system. We model a market where emitters get access and buy allowances from an auctioneer. In a posterior market, once demand levels are revealed, we model the actual trade of allowances among emitters (re-trading). We use the proposed model to study the Chilean \acrshort*{ndc} pledges (see also \cite{simsek_comparison_2020} for projections focused on demand by 2030 and a recent literature review), where we show that current efforts (budgets and carbon prices) are not sufficient to reach several of the \acrshort*{ndc} targets. Particularly, we demonstrate how a cap-and-trade system can be used alongside the concept of carbon budget to study energy system transitions that comply with countries' \acrshort*{ndc} targets.

\smallskip
The rest of the paper is structured as follows. Section \ref{sec:model} describes the model and the equilibrium concept. Section \ref{sec:calibration} presents the case study, data and calibration of the model. The results of our analysis are given in Section \ref{results} and Section \ref{sec:concl} concludes with the main findings.
