Figure~\ref{fig:mean_price} shows the resulting mean price of electricity over the period 2019-2050 for different carbon budgets and for each of the different demand scenarios. Independently of the carbon budget considered, higher demand scenarios always drive larger electricity prices. Also, note that electricity prices, for all demand scenarios, increase significantly with more restrictive carbon budgets. In fact, the increase is as high as 68\% ($\$91/$MWh to $\$154/$MWh) and 76\% (\$70$/$MWh to $\$123/$MWh) for the High GDP and High effort scenarios (high and low demand scenarios), respectively. Interestingly, the Electrification and Mid GDP demand scenarios have similar mean electricity price for less restrictive carbon budgets. Such behavior is explained by the offset effect observed in the demand patterns between these two scenarios before and after 2030.
\smallskip

In addition to the electricity price, we also analyze both, the carbon price and the carbon permit re-trading price (second stage price), as shown in Figures~\ref{fig:price_allo} and \ref{fig:price_trade}. The carbon price (first stage price) is conditional on the probability of the realization of each scenario $\omega$ (see \Appendix Equation~\ref{eq:pi_a_appendix}). In fact, facing uncertainty, emitting units must acquire emissions permits that would allow them to supply electricity for each of the possible realization of demand scenarios. Figure~\ref{fig:price_allo} shows such a price for different carbon budget scenarios. We observed prices ranging from 46 USD/\acrshort*{tco2e} to over 300 USD/\acrshort*{tco2e} when a carbon budget of 100 \acrshort*{mtco2e} is considered. Note that the prices obtained here are in good agreement with what authors have claimed is a suitably, efficient price for carbon emissions (for instance, see Table~1 from \cite{feijoo2019climate}). The carbon permit trading price paid by emitting units (re-trading market) is larger in the case of the High GDP scenario, with prices surpassing \$400 per \acrshort*{tco2e}. Furthermore, the trading price is in fact larger than the (first stage) carbon price paid by emitting generators in the scenarios that have high demand in later years, such as the High and Mid GDP scenarios. Trading prices in the electrification demand scenario are larger only in cases of carbon budgets larger than 500  \acrshort*{mtco2e}. Therefore, fossil based units that are allocated carbon permits could benefit by selling them if electricity demand does significantly expand. This is driven by the fact that generators consider high demand scenarios likely to occur, hence inducing a need for carbon permits that is not materialized when low electricity demand scenarios are realized. Indeed, high demand scenarios create scarcity of carbon permits, therefore, inducing larger prices. We also observe that carbon trading prices are subject to higher variability when low carbon budgets are considered. On the contrary, if lax carbon budgets are used, the impact on the carbon trading price is minimized.
\smallskip

The different carbon prices observed in each scenario (demand and carbon budget) also drive significant differences in capacity investment across technologies. Figure \ref{fig:cap_inv_add} depicts such differences by quantifying the additional capacity investments compared to the \acrshort*{bau} case (no carbon budget and hence no cap-and-trade policy) for each of the technology and demand scenarios. The range of investment when no carbon policy is implemented varies from 22.9 GW to 43.1 GW, according to the lowest and highest demand scenario (high effort - high GDP), respectively. Yet, when a carbon budget is considered, a significant increase on capacity investment is required. Additional capacity consists primarily on solar and wind energy, although hydro sources also show important additions when carbon policies become more stringent (right panel on Figure \ref{fig:cap_inv_add}). Altogether, imposing a limit on carbon emissions requires additional investments, ranging from 18 GW (in less stringent cases and low future demand levels) to 35 GW of capacity when severe policies are implemented. Interestingly, the High GDP scenario has similar levels of investment across different levels of carbon budget constraints. In fact, we observe a 3\% increase in capacity when a budget of 100 \acrshort*{mtco2e} is considered, compared to softer budgets, despite the large differences in emissions levels that are allowed. The reasoning behind this small difference in investments is observed on Figure \ref{fig:comp_100_1000}. We note that for the same demand level, a low carbon budget faces out coal and gas (main fossil fuel based emitters) right after 2020, whereas a larger budget faces out coal towards 2050, with a low share of natural gas still remaining. However, since the demand level in both cases is the same (an exogenous parameter), we obtain similar levels of renewable investment needed to satisfy demand by 2050. The slightly lower investment in the 1000 \acrshort*{mtco2e} scenario results from the small share of natural gas-fired power plants that are still in place. This suggests that under stricter carbon constraint and a high future demand, renewable energy will likely prevail due to increased cost of carbon allowances as well as the technology change of renewable sources. However, this effect is not shared by scenarios with low demand. Indeed, large differences in capacity investments can be observed for all other demand scenarios, particularly in the case of the High effort demand scenario, as depicted on Figure \ref{fig:cap_inv_add}.

