\section{Conclusions}
\label{sec:concl}

%The climate crisis urges for effective strategies and policies, and, one of the most effective is to establish emission targets to enforce the reduction of emissions of any industry.
This article discusses the implementation of a cap-and-trade system based on carbon budgets to achieve emission reduction targets. For this purpose, we present a two stage stochastic mixed complementarity capacity expansion model. The first stage of the model considers the allowance acquisition by emitting generators from an auctioneer (e.g., the government) while facing uncertainty regarding future electricity demand levels. The second stage considers the re-trading of allowances among emitters in a secondary market, once demand levels are revealed. The electricity market is cleared during both stages of the model. The modeling approach allows to obtain prices (electricity, carbon prices and re-trading) endogenously. 
\smallskip

The proposed model is used to analyze the Chilean electric sector and its capacity investment needs required to comply with energy and climate commitments. Results show that the carbon emissions reduction target set by the Chilean \acrshort*{ndc} is in fact an easy target and thus, highly insufficient. Furthermore, carbon prices obtained from our model are significantly higher than the current implemented carbon tax of 5 USD per \acrshort*{tco2e}. Therefore, the present strategy of the Chilean government for the electricity sector will likely have a limited impact and does not necessarily incentivizes investment in \acrshort*{ncre} sources. As an alternative, we identify different strategies that are aligned with the targets of phasing out coal or with the increased use of NCRE: 1) setting a severe carbon budget (500-600 \acrshort*{mtco2e} or smaller) which induces a high carbon price, enough to phase out coal in the near term, or 2) to have a slightly less severe carbon budget, which significantly increases the share \acrshort*{ncre} sources without completely phasing out coal. A third alternative that we explore correspond to (carbon) market segmentation. By defining endogenous caps on trading permits when the allowances are already distributed, coal phase out could be attained by 2035. Nevertheless, there is still the need of a more stringent carbon budget. There are relations of the endogenous caps with other variables that need further analysis, e.g., as the impact on prices, the role of inter-temporal substitution or the cost of stranded assets. 
%In this context, it is important to account for possible financial burden. Generally, the cost of stranded power plants are significant for developing economies, such as Chile or Latin America. Hence, it becomes extremely important to address the implications of policies and to improve the mitigation strategies. \smallskip

We also found that, when uncertainty is considered, high demand scenarios have carbon trading prices (second stage) larger than the price at which generators initially purchased carbon permits (first stage). Fossil-fueled generators hedged the risk of running low of permits by acquiring more carbon allowances. If such demand scenarios are not realized, generators sell the excess of permits at a lower price than what they had paid for. This effect poses risk measure and long-term investment behavior as an interesting feature for further analysis in our model. However, we recognized that this is just one possible feature, and that several other aspects can be considered, such as permit banking or different strategies for allowance allocation. Finally, we also found that, for all demand scenarios and all carbon budgets, the capacity investments is significantly larger than the case where no cap-and-trade policy is implemented. In all scenarios, the predominant technologies are Solar and Wind. However, when stricter policies are implemented (low carbon budget), the generation matrix becomes more diverse, as hydro technologies add significant generation capacity to account for the discontinued coal and gas based generators.

